I&#39;m trying to override / ignore the stacking context for an element so it can be positioned on the z-axis relative to the page root.  


However, according to the article [**What No One Told You About Z-Index**][z-index]:

&gt;If an element is contained in a stacking context at the bottom of the stacking order, there is no way to get it to appear in front of another element in a different stacking context that is higher in the stacking order, even with a z-index of a billion!
&gt;
&gt;New stacking contexts can be formed on an element in one of three ways:
&gt;
&gt;* When an element is the root element of a document (the &lt;html&gt; element)
&gt;* When an element has a position value other than static and a z-index value other than auto
&gt;* When an element has an opacity value less than 1

With the following example:

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: false babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-css --&gt;

    .red, .green, .blue { position: absolute; }
    .red   { background: red; }
    .green { background: green; }
    .blue  { background: blue; }

&lt;!-- language: lang-html --&gt;

    &lt;div&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;red&quot;&gt;Red&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
    &lt;div&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;green&quot;&gt;Green&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
    &lt;div&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;blue&quot;&gt;Blue&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

If the first div is given `opacity:.99;`, (which creates a [new stacking context][stacking] on the first node) then even **if `.red` has `z-index:1`, it will still be placed behind the other elements** because it is just rendered as the highest element within that stack.

[Working Demo in jsFiddle][fiddle]
====

Which looks like this:

![demo][demo]


**Q**: Is there a way for an element to ignore the stack context of any of it&#39;s parent elements and ask to be positioned relative to the original stack context of the page?

[z-index]: http://philipwalton.com/articles/what-no-one-told-you-about-z-index/

[stacking]: http://www.w3.org/TR/CSS2/zindex.html
[fiddle]: http://jsfiddle.net/KyleMit/b5Hz9/
[demo]: http://i.imgur.com/oLJ3JwZ.png

### Question

Can I dynamically ignore a property from a sealed class using [`System.Text.Json.JsonSerializer`][4]?



### Example Code

**Example class from another library**:

```cs
public sealed class FrozenClass
{
    // [JsonIgnore] &lt;- cannot apply because I don&#39;t own this class
    public int InternalId { get; set; }
    public string FirstName { get; set; }
    public string LastName { get; set; }
}
```

**Default Serialization**:

```cs
var person = new FrozenClass() { InternalId = 3, FirstName = &quot;Dorothy&quot;, LastName = &quot;Vaughan&quot; };
var jsonString = System.Text.Json.JsonSerializer.Serialize(person);
```

**Actual Outcome**:

```js
{ &quot;InternalId&quot;: 3, &quot;FirstName&quot;: &quot;Dorothy&quot;, &quot;LastName&quot;: &quot;Vaughan&quot; }
```

**Expected Outcome**:

```js
{ &quot;FirstName&quot;: &quot;Dorothy&quot;, &quot;LastName&quot;: &quot;Vaughan&quot; }
```


### Alternatives that don&#39;t work

There are two other questions on how to [add JsonIgnore at RunTime][1] &amp; [add dynamic property name for serialization][2], but both are targeted at [Newtonsoft&#39;s Json.NET][3] - and often reference [this extension method][5]


There are several ways to modify the way a class is serialized with the native `JsonSerializer`, but all seem to rely on modifying the underlying class:

* You can [exclude properties from serialization][6] by adding the [`[JsonIgnore]`][7] attribute to the original class
* You can [register a JsonConverter on a property][8] by adding the [`[JsonConverter]`][9] attribute to the original class

However, in my case, the class is from another library and cannot be extended

### Workarounds

A possible workaround is to create another exportable class and setup a mapper between them

```cs
public class MyFrozenClass
{
    public MyFrozenClass(FrozenClass frozen)
    {
        this.FirstName = frozen.FirstName;
        this.LastName = frozen.LastName;
    }
    public string FirstName { get; set; }
    public string LastName { get; set; }
}
```
```cs
var jsonString = System.Text.Json.JsonSerializer.Serialize(new MyFrozenClass(person));
```

[1]: https://stackoverflow.com/q/25157511/1366033
[2]: https://stackoverflow.com/q/50565358/1366033
[3]: https://www.newtonsoft.com/json
[4]: https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/api/system.text.json.jsonserializer
[5]: https://blog.rsuter.com/advanced-newtonsoft-json-dynamically-rename-or-ignore-properties-without-changing-the-serialized-class/
[6]: https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/standard/serialization/system-text-json-how-to#exclude-properties-from-serialization
[7]: https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/api/system.text.json.serialization.jsonignoreattribute
[8]: https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/standard/serialization/system-text-json-converters-how-to#registration-sample---jsonconverter-on-a-property
[9]: https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/api/system.text.json.serialization.jsonconverter-1

